  "text": "and E((u 0 , u 1 )) < 0, there is always a break-down in finite time i.e. T ± (u 0 , u 1 ) < ∞. He showed this by an \"obstruction\" type of argument. Recently Krieger-SchlagTȃtaru [CITATION_1] have constructed radial examples (N = 3), for which T ± (u 0 , u 1 ) < ∞. For (1) a classical argument due to Zakharov and Glassey [CITATION_2] , based on the virial identity, shows the same result as H. Levine's if |x| 2 |u 0 | 2 < ∞, E(u 0 ) < 0. Moreover, for both (1) and (2) , in the focusing case we have the following static solution",
